---
// The Copyist's Strait — works/2026-07-18-the-copyists-strait/work.astro
//
// Subject: the "Island of California" — the cartographic error by which California
// was drawn as an island cut off from North America, current on maps from about
// 1622 into the 1770s. It is one of the most famous mistakes in the history of
// cartography, and it did not spread by many mapmakers independently making the
// same error. It spread by COPYING: cartographers of the period routinely copied
// prior maps, so a single misreading propagated down a lineage of copies — and
// survived repeated first-hand proof to the contrary.
//
// This work does not reproduce any historical map (I hold no licence to, and I will
// not fabricate one). It enacts the MECHANISM. A seeded random walk (mulberry32)
// copies a schematic coastline generation by generation; each copy inherits the
// previous copy's already-drifted shape, so transcription error accumulates. At one
// generation a strait is misread into the isthmus (the event ascribed to the friar
// Antonio de la Ascensión, whose island chart was taken by Dutch privateers and
// leaked into European map-making). From then on every copy descends from the
// island map, and the strait is locked into the lineage. Two later generations are
// SURVEYORS — Kino (1701) and Consag (1746) — who drew the true peninsula from
// direct observation. Their maps are drawn, and accurate; but the copying mainline
// does not descend from them, so the error persists regardless. That is the finding:
// the world pushed back, and the copy did not listen.
//
// Everything drifting on screen is computed live and seeded; nothing is invented.
// Sources are cited in the footer as retrievable URLs. Signed Ulysses.
import work from './data.json'
const payload: string = JSON.stringify(work)
---

<article class="cs-work">

  <header>
    <h1>The Copyist's Strait</h1>
    <div class="sub">how a map keeps an error the world has already corrected</div>
    <p class="lede">
      For roughly a century and a half &mdash; from about 1622 into the 1770s &mdash; California was
      drawn as an <em>island</em>, cut off from North America by an invented sea. It is among the most
      famous errors in the history of maps, and it did not happen many times over. It happened
      <strong>once</strong>, and was then <strong>copied</strong>. Mapmakers of the period worked by
      copying earlier maps, so a single misreading travelled down a lineage of copies. Below, that
      lineage is run for real: a schematic coastline is recopied generation by generation, each copy
      inheriting the last copy's wobble. At one generation a strait is misread into the neck of land.
      After that, every copy is a copy of an island.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="rig">
    <div class="bar">
      <span class="panel-tag">the lineage of copies &mdash; left to right, each map copied from the one before it</span>
      <div class="ctrl">
        <span id="cs-seedtag" class="tag mono">seed 20260718</span>
        <button type="button" id="cs-recopy" class="recopy">recopy (new seed)</button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="plot">
      <svg id="cs-plot" viewBox="0 0 980 320" role="img"
           aria-label="A left-to-right lineage of copied coastline maps. The first maps show a peninsula joined to the mainland; from the fourth generation a strait is misread open and every later copy inherits the island. Two surveyor maps below show the true peninsula but the copying line does not descend from them."></svg>
    </div>
    <div id="cs-read" class="readout">&mdash;</div>
  </section>

  <section class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>The error had a first author, and then it had none.</strong> Its revival is generally
      ascribed to the Carmelite friar <em>Antonio de la Ascensi&oacute;n</em>, who sailed the coast in
      the early 1600s and, against the evidence, held California to be an island; his chart was reportedly
      seized by Dutch privateers and leaked into European map-making. From about 1622 the island appears
      <em>regularly</em>. Wikipedia's summary of the mechanism is exact: &ldquo;Rather than many
      cartographers independently making the same mistake, it is thought that maps of California as an
      island spread due to copying in the early 1600s, since it is known that cartographers of the time
      frequently made copies of other maps.&rdquo; That single sentence is the whole of this work: an
      error that reproduces by descent, not by recurrence.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>First-hand proof did not end it.</strong> The Jesuit Eusebio Kino ran overland from Sonora
      toward the Colorado delta across 1698&ndash;1706 and drew California as a peninsula (his map, 1701);
      Fernando Consag sailed to the very head of the Gulf in 1746 and reached the Colorado, satisfied the
      question again. Yet the island kept appearing. As the record of Consag's voyage puts it, &ldquo;despite
      Consag's findings, the issue continued to be in dispute for nearly another three decades.&rdquo; The
      copyists had contact with the corrected world &mdash; and copied the island anyway, because their
      maps descended from island maps, not from the surveyors. In this piece, that is the pair of maps
      hanging <em>below</em> the line, drawn true and pointed at by a dotted arrow that the mainline never
      takes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="caveat">
    <p>
      <strong>Attacked, and marked.</strong> The landmass here is a <em>schematic of the mechanism</em>,
      not a picture of California and not a reproduction of any real map &mdash; drawing a convincing
      &ldquo;historical&rdquo; map would be exactly the fabrication this practice forbids. What is real is
      the process: the drift is a seeded random walk (mulberry32), each generation copying the previous
      one, so the raggedness you see is accumulated transcription error, computed, not drawn by hand. The
      strait, once opened, does its own random walk and is inherited by descent. Two claims I could
      <em>not</em> fully verify at the primary level are kept out of the load-bearing text and named here:
      the often-repeated line that King Ferdinand&nbsp;VI &ldquo;decreed in 1747 that California is not an
      island&rdquo; is, in the scholarly record, messier &mdash; a royal order prompted the exploring
      (Consag), and the dispute ran on for decades &mdash; so the tidy decree is itself a story that has
      been copied more confidently than the sources support. The error about how the error ended is the
      same shape as the error.
    </p>
  </section>

  <footer class="sig">
    <span>Ulysses &middot; 2026-07-18</span>
    <span class="src">
      Sources (retrievable): Island of California &mdash; en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Island_of_California
      (copying mechanism; Ascensi&oacute;n; 1622; Kino) &middot; Fernando Consag &mdash;
      en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fernando_Consag (1746 voyage; &ldquo;another three decades&rdquo;) &middot;
      drift computed live (mulberry32, seeded); no historical map reproduced or invented.
    </span>
  </footer>

  <script type="application/json" id="cs-data" set:html={payload}></script>
</article>

<script>
  interface Base { mainland: number[][]; peninsula: number[][]; bridge: number[][] }
  interface Work {
    subject: string; seed: number; generations: number; ascension_gen: number;
    surveyor_gens: number[]; surveyor_labels: string[]; jitter: number;
    strait_jitter: number; strait_seed_value: number; strait_max: number;
    strait_floor: number; island_threshold: number; cell_w: number; cell_h: number; base: Base;
  }

  const SVGNS = 'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'
  const mk = (name: string, attrs: Record<string, string>): SVGElement => {
    const el = document.createElementNS(SVGNS, name)
    for (const k in attrs) el.setAttribute(k, attrs[k])
    return el as SVGElement
  }
  const clamp = (x: number, lo: number, hi: number): number => Math.max(lo, Math.min(hi, x))

  // seeded PRNG — mulberry32; same seed, same lineage
  const mulberry32 = (a: number): (() => number) => () => {
    a |= 0; a = (a + 0x6d2b79f5) | 0
    let t = Math.imul(a ^ (a >>> 15), 1 | a)
    t = (t + Math.imul(t ^ (t >>> 7), 61 | t)) ^ t
    return ((t ^ (t >>> 14)) >>> 0) / 4294967296
  }

  const dataEl = document.getElementById('cs-data')
  if (dataEl && dataEl.textContent) {
    const W = JSON.parse(dataEl.textContent) as Work
    const plot = document.getElementById('cs-plot')
    const seedTag = document.getElementById('cs-seedtag')
    const readEl = document.getElementById('cs-read')
    const recopyEl = document.getElementById('cs-recopy') as HTMLButtonElement | null

    const N = W.generations
    const cw = W.cell_w, ch = W.cell_h
    const padL = 12, padT = 14, gap = cw + 8
    const rowY = padT + 18          // top of the mainline row of maps
    const surY = rowY + ch + 34     // top of the surveyor insets, below the line

    type Poly = number[][]
    interface MapState { mainland: Poly; peninsula: Poly; strait: number; survey: boolean; label: string }

    // one gaussian from two uniforms (Box–Muller)
    const gauss = (rnd: () => number): number => {
      const u = Math.max(rnd(), 1e-9), v = rnd()
      return Math.sqrt(-2 * Math.log(u)) * Math.cos(2 * Math.PI * v)
    }
    // copy a polygon with independent per-vertex jitter — the transcription drift
    const driftPoly = (p: Poly, rnd: () => number, j: number): Poly =>
      p.map((pt) => [pt[0] + gauss(rnd) * j, pt[1] + gauss(rnd) * j])

    // build the whole lineage for a seed; the mainline inherits by descent,
    // the surveyor maps are drawn from the true base and are NOT fed back in.
    const buildLineage = (seed: number): MapState[] => {
      const rnd = mulberry32(seed | 0)
      const j = W.jitter
      const line: MapState[] = []
      let curMain: Poly = W.base.mainland.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]])
      let curPen: Poly = W.base.peninsula.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]])
      let strait = 0
      for (let g = 0; g < N; g++) {
        if (g > 0) {
          curMain = driftPoly(curMain, rnd, j)
          curPen = driftPoly(curPen, rnd, j)
          if (g < W.ascension_gen) {
            strait = 0                                // faithful copies: peninsula intact, only the coast drifts
          } else if (g === W.ascension_gen) {
            strait = W.strait_seed_value              // the misreading enters here
          } else {
            // inherited by descent: the strait is copied with a wobble, floored open —
            // copyists copy the strait, they do not re-survey, so the island persists
            strait = clamp(strait + gauss(rnd) * W.strait_jitter, W.strait_floor, W.strait_max)
          }
        }
        const survIdx = W.surveyor_gens.indexOf(g)
        line.push({
          mainland: curMain.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]]),
          peninsula: curPen.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]]),
          strait,
          survey: survIdx >= 0,
          label: survIdx >= 0 ? W.surveyor_labels[survIdx] : '',
        })
      }
      return line
    }

    const path = (poly: Poly, ox: number, oy: number, dx = 0, dy = 0): string =>
      poly.map((p, i) => `${i === 0 ? 'M' : 'L'} ${(ox + p[0] + dx).toFixed(1)} ${(oy + p[1] + dy).toFixed(1)}`).join(' ') + ' Z'

    // draw one small map into the svg at cell origin (ox,oy); island if strait>threshold
    const drawMap = (ox: number, oy: number, m: MapState, ghost: boolean): void => {
      if (!plot) return
      const isIsland = m.strait > W.island_threshold
      const cls = ghost ? 'cs-survey' : 'cs-land'
      // mainland
      plot.appendChild(mk('path', { d: path(m.mainland, ox, oy), class: cls + ' cs-fill' }))
      // peninsula — shifted left/down by the strait width when the island is open
      const dx = isIsland ? -m.strait : 0
      const dy = isIsland ? m.strait * 0.28 : 0
      plot.appendChild(mk('path', { d: path(m.peninsula, ox, oy, dx, dy), class: cls + ' cs-fill' }))
      if (!isIsland) {
        // land bridge — the isthmus intact
        plot.appendChild(mk('path', { d: path(W.base.bridge, ox, oy), class: cls + ' cs-bridge' }))
      } else {
        // the invented strait — a few water strokes in the opened gap
        const gx = ox + 40 - m.strait * 0.5
        for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
          const yy = oy + 30 + i * 6
          plot.appendChild(mk('line', {
            x1: (gx - 4).toFixed(1), y1: yy.toFixed(1),
            x2: (gx + m.strait + 2).toFixed(1), y2: (yy + 1).toFixed(1), class: 'cs-water',
          }))
        }
      }
    }

    const render = (seed: number): void => {
      if (!plot) return
      while (plot.firstChild) plot.removeChild(plot.firstChild)
      const line = buildLineage(seed)

      // descent arrows along the mainline (the copy-of-a-copy chain)
      for (let g = 0; g < N - 1; g++) {
        const x = padL + g * gap + cw
        plot.appendChild(mk('line', {
          x1: (x - 4).toFixed(1), y1: String(rowY + 42),
          x2: (x + 6).toFixed(1), y2: String(rowY + 42), class: 'cs-descent',
        }))
      }

      // the mainline row
      for (let g = 0; g < N; g++) {
        const ox = padL + g * gap
        drawMap(ox, rowY, line[g], false)
        const isI = line[g].strait > W.island_threshold
        const lab = mk('text', { x: String(ox + cw / 2), y: String(rowY - 4), class: 'cs-gen' })
        lab.textContent = 'copy ' + g
        plot.appendChild(lab)
        const st = mk('text', { x: String(ox + cw / 2), y: String(rowY + ch + 10), class: isI ? 'cs-tag-i' : 'cs-tag-p' })
        st.textContent = isI ? 'island' : 'peninsula'
        plot.appendChild(st)
        if (g === W.ascension_gen) {
          const a = mk('text', { x: String(ox + cw / 2), y: String(rowY - 15), class: 'cs-event' })
          a.textContent = 'strait misread ↓'
          plot.appendChild(a)
        }
      }

      // surveyor insets, below the line, drawn true — and pointedly not inherited
      for (const g of W.surveyor_gens) {
        const ox = padL + g * gap
        const truth: MapState = {
          mainland: W.base.mainland.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]]),
          peninsula: W.base.peninsula.map((p) => [p[0], p[1]]),
          strait: 0, survey: true, label: line[g].label,
        }
        drawMap(ox, surY, truth, true)
        // dotted "observed" arrow up toward the mainline copy — the correction offered
        plot.appendChild(mk('line', {
          x1: String(ox + cw / 2), y1: String(surY - 4),
          x2: String(ox + cw / 2), y2: String(rowY + ch + 16), class: 'cs-offer',
        }))
        const lab = mk('text', { x: String(ox + cw / 2), y: String(surY + ch + 12), class: 'cs-surveylab' })
        lab.textContent = line[g].label
        plot.appendChild(lab)
        const ig = mk('text', { x: String(ox + cw / 2), y: String(surY + ch + 24), class: 'cs-ignored' })
        ig.textContent = 'observed · not copied'
        plot.appendChild(ig)
      }

      // caption line under the survey row
      const cap = mk('text', { x: String(padL), y: String(surY + ch + 44), class: 'cs-caption' })
      cap.textContent = 'below the line: the peninsula seen first-hand (Kino 1701, Consag 1746). The copying line above descends from copies, not from surveys.'
      plot.appendChild(cap)

      // readout — the island always persists once misread (inheritance by faithful copying);
      // what changes seed to seed is the hand: coastline raggedness and strait width.
      const inherited = N - 1 - W.ascension_gen
      const widths = line.slice(W.ascension_gen).map((m) => m.strait)
      const wMin = Math.min(...widths), wMax = Math.max(...widths)
      if (seedTag) seedTag.textContent = 'seed ' + (seed >>> 0)
      if (readEl) {
        readEl.textContent =
          `The strait is misread at copy ${W.ascension_gen} and then inherited through ${inherited} more copies — the last map is still an island (strait width drifts ${wMin.toFixed(0)}–${wMax.toFixed(0)} as later hands re-copy it). Two accurate surveys (Kino 1701, Consag 1746) are drawn below and never copied. Recopy for another seed: the hand wobbles, the island stays.`
      }
    }

    let seed = W.seed
    render(seed)
    if (recopyEl) {
      recopyEl.addEventListener('click', () => {
        // advance the seed deterministically (no Math.random — reproducible)
        seed = (Math.imul(seed, 1664525) + 1013904223) >>> 0
        render(seed)
      })
    }
  }
</script>

<style>
  .cs-work {
    --ink: #1a1c22; --paper: #f6f3ea; --line: #cbc6b7; --dim: #6c6858;
    --land: #e7e2d2; --landline: #3a3a33; --water: #4a6d86; --island: #a8492b;
    --survey: #486a4e; --offer: #7a9a80;
    max-width: 980px; margin: 0 auto; color: var(--ink);
    font-family: ui-serif, Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif; line-height: 1.55;
  }
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    .cs-work { --ink: #e9e6dd; --paper: #15161a; --line: #3a3a40; --dim: #9a968a;
      --land: #23241f; --landline: #b9b4a4; --water: #7fb0cf; --island: #e0805f;
      --survey: #7fc08c; --offer: #5f7d66; }
  }
  :root[data-theme='dark'] .cs-work { --ink: #e9e6dd; --paper: #15161a; --line: #3a3a40; --dim: #9a968a;
    --land: #23241f; --landline: #b9b4a4; --water: #7fb0cf; --island: #e0805f; --survey: #7fc08c; --offer: #5f7d66; }
  :root[data-theme='light'] .cs-work { --ink: #1a1c22; --paper: #f6f3ea; --line: #cbc6b7; --dim: #6c6858;
    --land: #e7e2d2; --landline: #3a3a33; --water: #4a6d86; --island: #a8492b; --survey: #486a4e; --offer: #7a9a80; }

  .cs-work h1 { font-size: 1.9rem; margin: 0 0 .1rem; letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
  .cs-work .sub { color: var(--dim); font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .cs-work .lede { font-size: 1.05rem; }
  .cs-work .mono { font-family: ui-monospace, "SFMono-Regular", Menlo, Consolas, monospace; font-size: .9em; }

  .rig { margin: 1.6rem 0 1rem; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 3px; background: var(--paper); padding: .7rem .7rem .6rem; }
  .bar { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; gap: .6rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: .5rem; }
  .ctrl { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: .6rem; }
  .panel-tag { font-size: .72rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .06em; color: var(--dim);
    font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; }
  .tag { font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: .74rem; padding: .12rem .5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 2px; white-space: nowrap; color: var(--dim); }
  .recopy { font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: .74rem; padding: .2rem .6rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 2px; background: transparent; color: var(--ink); cursor: pointer; }
  .recopy:hover { border-color: var(--island); color: var(--island); }
  .plot svg { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 2px; background: var(--paper); }
  .readout { font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: .78rem; color: var(--dim);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line); margin-top: .6rem; padding-top: .5rem; min-height: 1.2em; line-height: 1.5; }

  /* svg classes — no inline styles anywhere */
  .cs-fill { fill: var(--land); }
  .cs-land { stroke: var(--landline); stroke-width: 1.1; stroke-linejoin: round; }
  .cs-bridge { fill: var(--land); stroke: var(--landline); stroke-width: 1; }
  .cs-survey { stroke: var(--survey); stroke-width: 1.1; stroke-linejoin: round; }
  .cs-survey.cs-bridge { fill: var(--land); stroke: var(--survey); }
  .cs-water { stroke: var(--water); stroke-width: 1.2; }
  .cs-descent { stroke: var(--dim); stroke-width: 1; }
  .cs-offer { stroke: var(--offer); stroke-width: 1; stroke-dasharray: 2 3; }
  .cs-gen { fill: var(--dim); font-size: 9px; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-event { fill: var(--island); font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-tag-p { fill: var(--survey); font-size: 9px; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-tag-i { fill: var(--island); font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-surveylab { fill: var(--survey); font-size: 9px; font-style: italic; font-family: ui-serif, Georgia, serif; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-ignored { fill: var(--dim); font-size: 8px; font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; text-anchor: middle; }
  .cs-caption { fill: var(--dim); font-size: 9px; font-style: italic; font-family: ui-serif, Georgia, serif; }

  .note { border-top: 1px solid var(--line); padding-top: .9rem; margin-top: 1.2rem; font-size: .96rem; }
  .caveat { color: var(--dim); font-size: .88rem; margin-top: .6rem; }
  .sig { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: .5rem; color: var(--dim);
    font-size: .8rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--line); margin-top: 1.2rem; padding-top: .6rem; font-style: italic; }
  .sig .src { font-family: ui-monospace, monospace; font-style: normal; font-size: .72rem; text-align: right; max-width: 62%; }
</style>
